ort a `variant` prop. Passing `variant=\"destructive\"` will result in an invalid attribute warning in the console and will not apply the destructive styles (red text and hover background).\n\nInstead, apply the destructive styles conditionally using the `className` prop.\n\n```suggestion\n              {group.map((action) =&gt; (\n                &lt;DropdownMenuItem\n                  key={action.label}\n                  disabled\n                  className={action.destructive ? \"text-destructive focus:bg-destructive/15 focus:text-destructive\" : \"\"}\n                &gt;\n```\n```\n\n**Thread 5**\n- threadId: `PRRT********UyQ9`\n- commentId: `3522935138`\n- path: `apps/web/app/(chat)/components/chat-list-sidebar/index.tsx`\n- line: 33\n- author: `gemini-code-assist`\n- isResolved: false / isOutdated: false\n- severity: medium\n- body:\n```\nSince `isMobile` is initialized to `false` on the server and during the initial client paint (to match SSR), `ChatListSidebar` will always mount and render the sidebar and `ChatList` on mobile first. Once the `useEffect` inside `useSidebar` runs and sets `isMobile` to `true`, the component re-renders and returns `null`.\n\nThis causes the `ChatList` component to briefly mount and execute its query subscriptions on mobile before immediately unmounting.\n\nTo prevent this unnecessary query execution and completely avoid hydration mismatches, introduce a `mounted` state and only render the sidebar after the component has mounted on desktop.\n\n*Note: Remember to import `useState` and `useEffect` from 'react' at the top of the file.*\n\n```suggestion\nexport function ChatListSidebar() {\n  const { isMobile } = useSidebar();\n  const startNewChat = useStartNewChat();\n  const [mounted, setMounted] = useState(false);\n\n  useEffect(() =&gt; {\n    setMounted(true);\n  }, []);\n\n  if (!mounted || isMobile) {\n    return null;\n  }\n```\n```\n\n**Thread 6**\n- threadId: `PRRT********Uy9l`\n- commentId: `3522938312`\n- path: `app