 A pnpm-v11-specific variant involving `enableGlobalVirtualStore` ([#93556](https://github.com/vercel/next.js/issues/93556)) doesn't apply — you're on pnpm 10. No action needed, just be aware if `next dev` ever crashes with that specific error after a patch bump.\n- **`transpilePackages` is still correct alongside Turbopack**, not superseded by it. The package-bundling guide still lists it as the mechanism for un-prebuilt monorepo/node_modules packages ([transpilePackages docs](https://github.com/vercel/next.js/blob/canary/docs/01-app/03-api-reference/05-config/01-next-config-js/transpilePackages.mdx)); Turbopack doesn't have a \"handle workspace packages automatically\" replacement for it.\n- **`proxy.ts`** is the correct 16.0 rename target (`middleware.ts` → `proxy.ts`, exported fn `middleware` → `proxy`); confirmed still current in the 16.2.10 docs. Note `edge` runtime is **not supported** in `proxy` — it's forced to `nodejs` — so if your cookie gate ever needed edge runtime you'd have to stay on `middleware.ts`. Config flags renamed too (e.g. `skipMiddlewareUrlNormalize` → `skipProxyUrlNormalize`) — check if you use any.\n\n### Recommended\n\n1. **Enable Turbopack persistent build caching + adjust CI cache paths** (biggest lever for your setup). `turbopackFileSystemCacheForBuild` reached general availability as an opt-in flag; it's what actually makes `.next/cache` meaningful for Turbopack builds in CI (previously Turbopack's own build cache wasn't disk-persisted the way webpack's was). Vercel's own benchmarks: 2.3×–5.5× faster warm builds ([16.3 Turbopack blog](https://nextjs.org/blog/next-16-3-turbopack)).\n   ```ts\n   // next.config.ts / apps/web/next.config.mjs\n   const nextConfig = {\n     experimental: {\n       turbopackFileSystemCacheForBuild: true,\n     },\n   }\n   ```\n   Your Turborepo build task currently caches `.next/**` minus `.next/cache/**` — that exclusion made sense pre-16.3 when Turbopack's build cache wasn't meaningfully warm-restorable,